column47: Expressions of Interest for Partners for the ACS and STP Development Partner Framework
column48:
NHS Arden & GEM Commissioning Support Unit is looking for a co-venture partner or partners who can join forces and combine strengths to build an effective multi response to NHS England's ACS and STP Development Partner Framework. 

We have secured over 100m of new business over the last couple of years (including recently in Norfolk & Waveney CSU Support - Corporate IT and GP IT services in Essex - Global Digital Exemplar NHS England Clinical Registry and our Mental Health work - Coming Home) and continue to build strong relationships throughout the system at all levels - ACS leaders, CCG and NHS Trust leadership.

In responding to the opportunities that will be presented by the new framework we are wanting to get into a serious dialogue with a partner or partners who we can work closely together with over the coming months and years, to pool experience and expertise to create a compelling Population Health Management offer to the wider health and social system.

AGCSU are seeking expressions of interest from suppliers to potentially 'Co-Bid' or form some other close working relationship with as part of our response to the ACS and STP Development Partner Framework. We are particularly looking for partners who we can work with across the following lots:

 1 - Digitising care & operation services (inc. EPR) - however, not due for NHS England framework tender until mid-2018
 2a - Local health and care records (strategy/implementation support
 2b - Local health and care records (Infrastructure)
 5 - Informatics analytics and digital tools to support system planning and evaluation
 6 - Transformation and change support
 7 - Patient empowerment & activation
 8 - Demand management & capacity planning
 9 - System assurance support 

We do not underestimate the opportunity that the framework (and call-offs) will bring to work with local health economies to bring advanced capabilities to make faster improvements in the quality of care and the health. This will help the well-being of their population and help drive the required cultural shift across clinicians and managers to use data in more meaningful ways . 

As a Commissioning Support Unit (CSU) we have good experience and a depth of knowledge in a number of areas but recognise that we are not a market leader in some of the advanced capabilities. Our business offer has some well-refined, implemented and working solutions, backed up by years of experience working with and supporting local clinicians and managers to reform the system. We have developed specialist knowledge in some of the more complex aspects of data management and sharing, including IG compliance. We are also increasingly branching out into more progressive capabilities as we work with partners to digitally transform our existing customer base, for example through command centres, predictive analytics and technologies to empower and connect to patients.

Additional information: By way of additional insight - NHS Arden & GEM Commissioning Support Unit (AGCSU) is one of the largest CSUs in the country. We act as a valued and trusted partner for commissioners, local authorities and providers to tackle the challenges they face in building integrated, high-quality, cost-effective services that lead to better health outcomes for patients. Our valued proposition includes:

 A broad range and depth of experience - with a team of over 1,000 staff, we provide a range of specialist expertise as well as real insights and learnings from the services we deliver to our customers
 Insight and analytical capabilities - we have one of the largest information service teams in the country, recognised nationally for our data processing capabilities. We host various data platforms on behalf of CCGs and NHS England, including the National Commissioning Data Repository (NCDR), which holds the entire countries commissioning data
 Impact and intervention - building upon the insight we have about our customers, we develop innovative and transformational solutions that address the local system needs. We have award winning transformation and procurement teams who work extensively, as trusted partners, with commissioners, local authorities and providers that enhance and develop solutions to meet the new models of care agenda and deliver better outcome for our citizens

Please register your interest on the Arden & GEM Bravo Solution e-procurement portal at: https://ardengemcsu.bravosolution.co.uk (registration and use of the website is free of charge). 

Express interest by: 
1. Logging-in to the Arden GEM CSU e-Tendering portal 
2. Select Open Access PQQ 
3. Search for PQQ 457 related to this expression of interest and view details 
4. Click on Express Interest link 
5. Once you have expressed interest, access the My PQQs page

Once registered, please complete the 'Response Template' identifying the specific lots you are interested in and a brief profile of your organisation and experience and submit via the qualification envelope. The deadline for submitting a response for this market engagement exercise is 17.00pm on 8th January 2018. 

Please note that this is a market engagement exercise and not a PQQ or procurement exercise. We are using this functionality within the Bravo portal to communicate and engage with interested parties. Any future opportunities regarding this service will be formally advertised via a contract notice and interested parties will be required to apply.

*Business-to-business data - Data is purchased for the Education Marketing department to assist Red Cross Training in the achievement of their annual sales target for workplace first aid training. Specific marketing objectives of using this data are to increase new business and customer acquisition; identify prospect marketing segmentation strategies amongst UK businesses; develop and implement targeted marketing campaigns to key business sectors; and analyse the effectiveness of marketing campaigns amongst key segments in terms of ROI, reach and engagement; and

Durham University is a research-intensive university that prides itself on providing an education and wider student experience that is on par with the very best institutions worldwide.  We have been developing a new University Strategy that sets out our aims to ensure that we are world-leading in research and engagement, education, and the wider student experience.

Part of the implementation of this new strategy involves an extensive period of service review and improvement. As part of this exercise the University will be revising its overarching operating model for its professional services as well as reviewing and improving a number of strategic processes.
The pilot phase (phase 1) of the programme, which consisted of the development of a high level Target Operating Model for the University and a pilot approach to process review within a single functional area (Human Resources) is now complete. We will now continue this work into Phase 2, focusing on the design and implementation of new operating models and detailed process reviews within all professional services areas. This programme of work will benefit from the involvement of an external partner who will be able to: a. validated target operating models for professional services areas and supporting implementation plans (to be produced in partnership with project sponsors) b. an agreed method for training on process reviews, including briefing in-house staff c. outputs from the process reviews including: i. a clear picture of current state processes ii. recommended future state processes with the benefit of the insight of those working in the business area iii. identified benefits and savings iv. a costed operating model for this business v. any interdependencies with IT systems or other projects vi. a recommended approach to the implementation of the new process d. a programme team trained in the methods and techniques used by the provider e. an evaluation of the programme.
The work is likely to be varied and require involvement with staff at differing levels of seniority and expertise.

column47: Assessment of the potential to reduce UK F-gas emissions beyond the ambition of the F-gas Regulation and Kigali Amendment
column48:
The CCC and carbon budget advice
The Committee on Climate Change was set up as part of the Climate Change Act. The Committee is an independent body tasked with providing advice to government on climate change issues, and particularly the setting of carbon budgets for the UK. 

The CCC's advice on carbon budgets is based on detailed modelling of a range of technologies and behaviours that could be deployed across the economy. Using that modelling, CCC has developed scenarios for deployment of technologies to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to 2020 , 2030  and to 2050 . These are intended to demonstrate possible ways in which carbon budgets and the 2050 target could be met, estimate the economic cost of doing so, and identify barriers to delivery and consider how these could be overcome. 
F-gas reduction in the CCC's scenarios
The CCC's scenarios for meeting the fifth carbon budget set out a 68% cut in F-gas emissions from 2015 to 2030, involving reductions in emissions from refrigeration, air conditioning in buildings and vehicles and aerosols.  However, the evidence base in this area is old and likely outdated. This has limited the CCC's capacity to assess whether there is potential for the Government to implement policy that goes beyond the existing F-gas Regulation. In 2015 and 2016, we recommended that the Government investigate opportunities to go beyond the EU regulatory minimums on F-gases. The Government has not made progress on this.

*** Please see specification for more information ***

column47: Engagement with potential bidders for Provision of an APMS contract for the Community Health Centre
column48:
Midlands & Lancashire Commissioning Support Unit (ML CSU) on behalf of the Commissioners, Leicester City Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG), would like to invite providers to attend an Early Suppliers Involvement (ESI) event to inform the service specification for the upcoming procurement of an APMS contract for the Community Health Centre located at Melbourne Road in Leicester city.

The Commissioners would like to hear from any potential provider who would be willing to present and discuss their current and future service delivery models, capability and capacity, to help finalise the service specification and to ensure alignment and discussion of potential innovation processes.

The Commissioners would value expert insight that can be given into the delivery of this type of service and information would be greatly received. The information you provide and your details may be used in the rationale for the service specification final content.

The event will take place in Leicester from 2pm-4pm on the 11th of January 2018. (full address: Sure Start, Children Young People and Family Centre Room 20 Barnard Cl, Leicester LE2 0UZ)

The session will be a workshop-style format of to allow for informal discussion on the relevant topics.
Topics for discussion:
-	Service specification 
-	KPI's
-	Patient access 
-	Patients involvement and education 


If you are interested in meeting with the Commissioners please can you contact Paulo Cabral, Senior Procurement Officer, on paulo.cabral@nhs.net  with the following details by no later than 5pm Wednesday 5th January 2018:

 Name of delegates
 Job title of delegates
 Organisation details, including address
 Delegate email address and telephone number.

Places are strictly limited therefore reservations are restricted to no more than 2 persons per organisation. The event is likely/will take place at St. Johns House in Leicester City CCG facilities.


A further advertisement will be published notifying providers of a planned market engagement event in the near future. The advert will also be placed on Contracts Finder), and on MLCSUs' procurement portal, Bravo, which will be utilised for the tender. Therefore, we recommend that you register with both of these websites in the meantime at: 
https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk
https://mlcsu.bravosolution.co.uk/.

Additional information: "Light Touch Regime" services
This procurement is for clinical services which are Light Touch Regime services for the purpose of the Public Contracts Regulations 2015 as specified in Schedule 3 of the Regulations ("Regulations"). Accordingly, the contracting authorities are only bound by those parts of the Regulations detailed in Chapter 3 Particular Procurement Regimes Section 7. The contracting authorities are not voluntarily following any other part of the Regulations.  
The procedure which the contracting authorities are following is set out in the MOI and ITT. As the CCG is a relevant body for the purpose of the National Health Service (Procurement, Patient Choice and Competition) (No 2) Regulations 2013 these Regulations also apply to this procurement. 

Right to Cancel
The contracting authority reserves the right to discontinue the procurement process at any time, which shall include the right not to award a contract or contracts, and does not bind itself to accept the lowest tender, or any tender received, and reserves the right to award a contract in part, or to call for new tenders should it consider this necessary. The contracting authority shall not be liable for any costs or expenses incurred by any candidate or tenderer in connection with the completion and return of the information requested in this Contract Notice, or in the completion or submission of any tender, irrespective of the outcome of the competition or if the competition is cancelled or postponed. All dates, time periods and values specified in this notice are provisional and the contracting authority reserves the right to change these. 

Transparency
The contracting authority is subject to the Freedom of Information Act 2000 (FOIA) and the Environmental Information Regulations 2004 (EIR) and may be required to disclose information received in the course of this procurement under FOIA or the EIR. In addition, and in accordance with the UK Government's policies on transparency, the contracting authority intends to publish procurement documentation and the text of any resulting contractual arrangements, subject to possible redactions at the discretion of the contracting authority. Any redactions, whether in relation to information requests under FOIA, the EIR or policies on transparency will be in accordance with those grounds prescribed under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 and the Environmental Information Regulations 2004. Further information on transparency can be found at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/procurement-and-contracting-transparency-requirements-guidance

To register on the Bravo portal

column47: A rehabilitation day centre to support people affected by brain injury
column48:
Brain injury affects the way a person thinks, learns and remembers. Different mental abilities are located in different parts of the brain, so a head injury can damage some, but not necessarily all, skills such as speed of thought, memory, understanding, and concentration, solving problems and using language. 
Communication problems after brain injury are very common. Everyone who has had a head injury can be left with some changes in emotional reaction and behaviour. Executive dysfunction is a term for the range of cognitive, emotional and behavioural difficulties which often occur after injury to the frontal lobes of the brain. Impairment of executive functions is common after acquired brain injury and has a profound effect on many aspects of everyday life.
The service will provide a day centre as a base to-
	Help service user set and achieve a series of measured goals. 
	Where appropriate support service users to move on from the service to more independent community based services. 
	Provide cognitive therapy for service users. 
	Work with service users to help them to reach their potential after a brain injury. 
	Liaise with and utilise other organisations and networks to improve outcomes for the service user.
	Ensure activities and goals are aligned with outcomes identified within care and support plans.
	Ensure information about the service is up to date on the local directory of services (My Care My Support).
	Complete quarterly monitoring returns. 
	The successful provider will be required to attend provider meetings organised by the Commissioner.
	Actively involve service users in the design of service delivery. 
	The successful bidder will have to track service user's progress against agreed goals in the short, medium and long term. 
	The successful provider will be required to work closely with Healthwatch.
	Develop and maintain referral routes with (including but not limited to) GPs, Occupational Therapists, Hospital, Social Workers and Adult Mental Health Services.
	Work with relevant clinical team (s)

column47: SDC - Provision of Temporary Accommodation Service
column48:
Stratford-on-Avon District Council has a legal obligation to provide accommodation for certain households that are either homeless or threatened with homelessness.  
      
      The main duties of the Council in respect of homeless households are detailed within the Housing Act 1996 Part VII and the Homeless Reduction Act 2017 (due to be implemented April 2018). The bulk of these households are eligible for Council assistance but not in need of substantial support, however, a minority will present a range of challenges in respect of their health, disability, capability, financial capacity and general vulnerability.
      
      The Contract between the Council and the Provider will be in two parts:
      
      1. To sub lease 24 properties (and it is anticipated a further 8 properties within 6 months from the commencement of the Contract) identified by the Council for use as temporary accommodation and a management and repairs service for households temporarily resident in those properties.
      
      2. For housing related support to be provided (where appropriate) to the homeless households in temporary accommodation to enable their homelessness claim to be processed swiftly, to enable them to secure accommodation and assist with the Council's duties under the Homelessness Reduction Act (when implemented), to address any barriers to move on, improve tenancy preparedness and prevent escalation of need to assist households to maintain and sustain accommodation. 
      
      Temporary accommodation is to be provided whilst investigations into homelessness applications are carried out and until such time as any duty to house is discharged. Temporary accommodation may also be used to assist with duties under the Homelessness Reduction Act or in exercise of a power, e.g. to house pending an appeal to the County Court.
      
      All temporary accommodation must comply with the Lettable Standard (see Appendix 2), terms if the sub-lease as well as the provisions specified in this Specification.
      
      Particular importance is placed by the Council on optimum occupancy levels and the Provider must deliver efficient, cost effective, statutorily compliant arrangements, including for the ending of occupation and re-letting of units once void.

      Background 
      Unitas Stoke-on-Trent Limited (Unitas) is a wholly owned subsidiary of Stoke-on-Trent City Council, which was established in March 2017 to deliver repairs and maintenance services for the Council's housing stock and public buildings, following the end of the current joint venture partnership with Kier Stoke Limited (Kier Stoke). The joint venture with Kier Stoke ends at midnight on 3 February 2018 at which point Unitas will commence delivering the services. 
      
      Introduction 
      A number of contractor frameworks are now being procured to support Unitas in the delivery of its repairs and maintenance obligations.   
      
      This Framework, known as the Labour-only Trades Framework, is being procured to support Unitas in the delivery of its response repairs. Whilst Unitas will have directly employed tradespeople, it is important to procure competent tradespeople to assist during periods of peak demand. 
      
      Contractors on this framework will be utilised on a labour only basis and paid on an agreed day rate.
      
      About the Labour-only Trades Framework 
      There are 12 lots and contractors can apply for one or multiple lots. Up to five contractors will be appointed to each lot and works will be awarded on a rotational basis. 
      
      Valid for four years, it is anticipated that the framework will commence on 4 September 2017, as Unitas has responsibility for some repairs and maintenance works which fall outside of the Kier Stoke Joint Venture.
      
      Both Stoke-on-Trent City Council and Unitas Stoke Ltd. will be able to utilise this framework.

column47: Market Engagement Event for GP Services (APMS) for Sollershot Surgery, Letchworth Garden City
column48:
NHS Arden and Greater East Midlands CSU (AGCSU), on behalf of NHS England Midlands & East (Central Midlands) and East & North Hertfordshire CCG (the Commissioners), would like to inform the market of the intention to procure Alternative Provider of Medical Services for Sollershott Surgery, Letchworth Garden City, Hertfordshire, SG6 3JW.

The Commissioners would like to invite providers to a Market Engagement event at 11.30am on Tuesday 9th January 2017. Further information will be circulated to delegates once the registration process closes at 15:00 on the 5th January 2018.

The actual patient list size was 5208 (October 2017) . These services must be GP Led and provided by GPs, nurses and other clinical professionals or healthcare workers, the successful Provider will be expected to: -Provide primary care services which will be accessible, convenient and responsive -Deliver all services throughout core hours Monday - Friday 8am-6:30pm -Design services around the needs of patients and carers, ensuring they are offered more choice and a greater say in their treatment -Have processes in place to evaluate and continually improve on patient satisfaction -Have processes in place to engage effectively with the local communities -Participate in National Quality and Outcomes Framework (QOF) -Be eligible for and expected to provide all Enhanced Services, remunerated in line with the relevant Directions as specified by the commissioner on an annual basis. -Promotion of healthy living with the aim of tackling the underlying causes of ill health.

The initial contract period will be 3 years, with the option to extend for a further 2 years (maximum term of 5 years). The anticipated financial envelope for Sollershott is approximately 2,445,973 over the lifetime of the contract (5 years), with the opportunity to earn extra income via QOF and CCG GP Enhanced Commissioning Framework. Transitional funding will be available in the first year.

This opportunity will be open to the entire market, including the current providers. It is intended that the tender will be published in mid-January 2018. As this tender is for existing services, the services must be fully operational by the service commencement date of 1st July 2018 in order to ensure continuity of care for patients.

The Commissioners would particularly welcome interest from forward thinking prospective providers wanting to deliver primary care services in a different way, working with the Commissioners and using the various significant support streams available and opportunities for local partnership working. East & North Herts CCG has substantial support programmes and resources in place to support clinical quality improvement, workforce development and technological solutions designed to release clinical time and enhance efficiency.

Additional information: 
NHSE and the East and North Herts CCG are committed to achieving both provider resilience and high quality care and access on a sustainable basis. The Commissioners will work with the provider during the tenure of the contract to explore and support innovation and change to help achieve these goals.

An expression of interest in this market event will not automatically entitle involvement in any future procurement exercise. The subsequent procurement will be advertised separately and all organisations wanting to participate will need to respond to the procurement advertisement when published.

To express an interest for the Market Engagement Event (9th January 2017) please: i) Register on the portal https://ardengemcsu.bravosolution.co.uk. ii) Express interest by a) logging-in to the AGCSU e-Tendering portal b) selecting response to advert and PQQ (ref: pqq_451), c) select Open Access PQQ, d) search for and access listing related to this contract and view details e) click on Express Interest link. iii) Once you have expressed interest, access the My PQQs page where you can complete the questionnaire. You must then submit your reply using the 'Submit Response' button at the top of the page. If you require any further assistance consult the on-line help/contact the helpdesk; Phone:0800 368 4850 E-mail help@bravosolution.co.uk

The Deadline to register for a place at the market engagement event is 15:00 Friday 5th January 2018

Please note that THIS IS NOT A PQQ, we are using this functionality within the Bravo portal to communicate with interested parties.

column48:
ESPO 664 Framework mini Competition. Lot 5.
      
      1 Introduction 
      2 Transport for the South East (TfSE) is a newly established shadow sub-national transport body representing 16 Local Transport Authorities (LTAs) and five Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs) in the South East .  
      
      3 The aim of TfSE is to support and grow the economy in the South East by identifying and prioritising a programme of strategic transport interventions. It also aims to improve the experience of the travelling public and businesses and bring about more reliable journeys free of congestion, whilst safeguarding the environment.   
      
      4 The key mechanism for expressing how TfSE will realise its vision and strategic priorities will be through its transport strategy to provide the basis for making recommendations on priorities for transport investment in the region. A route map for the development of the transport strategy has been produced setting out the work packages that will need to be completed to produce the transport strategy. 
      
      5 The initial stage of the transport strategy route map is an economic connectivity review.  This is intended to build on existing evidence and previous studies to provide an overarching view of the region's economic geography and functionality and transport's role within it. Critically, it will ensure that the transport strategy is grounded in the key issues around the economic impact of improved connectivity recognising that the region comprises a range of distinct functional economic areas. 
      
      6 This Invitation to Tender is being issued as a Further Competition under Lot 5 Highways Transport and Logistics of ESPO's Consultancy Services Framework (reference 664_17) to undertake the economic connectivity review. Separate invitations to tender consisting of one or more of the other work packages shown on the route map in the tender documents.

column47: Supported Accommodation for 16-18 Year Olds in Care
column48:
Cambridgeshire County Council and Peterborough City Council are going to be undertaking a procurement exercise in the Spring of 2018 for Supported Accommodation services for our 16-18 year olds who are in care, as our current framework contracts will end in 2018.

Before we go out to tender, we would like to invite Providers to an event to discuss the services we hope to procure, and to give you some information about the timelines involved, and the outcomes we hope to achieve through re-tendering these services. The event will be split into 2 sessions:

Morning session (10-12, for everyone to attend). To include:
	Background information about the scope of the tendering exercise, the context, an overview of the anticipated demand for these services, budget and the procurement timeline and processes.
	Some small, group activities looking at specific elements of the service and how best to design a service for Cambridgeshire and Peterborough to achieve the best outcomes for our young people aged 16-18 who need this type of accommodation.


Afternoon session (1-3pm specifically looking at the support needs of Unaccompanied Asylum Seeking Children). To include:
	Background information about the anticipated demand for these services
	Some small, group activities looking at specific elements of the service and how best to design a service for Cambridgeshire and Peterborough to achieve the best outcomes for our UASC young people aged 16-18 who need this type of accommodation.


More information, including an agenda and venue details (directions, parking etc.) will follow, but please hold the date in your diaries for this event.

We would be grateful if you could confirm your attendance by emailing CFA.AccessToResourcesAdmin@cambridgeshire.gov.uk by Friday 2nd February.

Please indicate when you respond whether you wish to attend the morning session only or the morning and the afternoon. Please also be advised that there will be a limit of 2 attendees per Provider, in order to ensure that every organisation that wants to attend, can.

column46: CCB WW1 grant evaluation award notice
column47: First World War Centenary Cathedral Repairs Fund Evaluation
column48:
The first 20 million of the government's First World War Centenary Cathedral Repairs fund was announced by the Chancellor in the March 2014 Budget and set up with the following objectives:

	To carry out necessary repair works to the fabric of the listed Anglican and Catholic cathedral churches in England. The works should be necessary to keep the building wind-proof and weather-tight, safe and open to the public.

	To carry out repairs to prevent further deterioration of the fabric of the listed building.

	To ensure the listed buildings are in a good and safe state of repair in order to host events commemorating the First World War.

A further 20 million was announced in the March 2016 Budget with the same objectives. 

The Fund is administered by the Cathedrals and Church Buildings Division (CCB, also known as ChurchCare) of the Archbishops' Council of the Church of England, on behalf of the Department of Culture, Media and Sport. 

In total 146 grants have been awarded to 57 Anglican and Catholic Cathedrals. The Fund has supported 133 separate projects (NB some projects received more than one grant).

The grant applications were assessed by an Expert Panel against the grant objectives, using the following criteria:

	The urgency of the work.

	The contribution of the project to keeping the cathedral safe and open.

	The financial need of the cathedral.

	The impact the completion of this project would have on the cathedral's overall maintenance and repairs programme. This criterion was intended to see where these grants could have maximum impact.

The objectives of the evaluation are:

	To assess how far the grants have met the Fund's objectives and criteria (see above).

	To assess the wider economic impact of the funding, including impact of the fund on the state of the specialist building industry, e.g. numbers employed, training enabled (including apprenticeships) in traditional craft skills, how easy was it to obtain tenders, impact on local pricing of e.g. scaffolding. This assessment should differentiate between cathedrals with and without in-house works teams.

	To obtain information about the wider community benefits of the funding, e.g. in terms of enabling community activity such as knowledge/learning about the Cathedral and First World War, First World War commemoration and other activies. This will including the ability to reallocate funds towards community activities which would otherwise have been allocated towards repair works.

	To enable learning about what worked well and what worked less well about the grant processes, to inform future cathedral repair funding initiatives. 

	To identify how far the grant programme has gone towards meeting the identified long-term maintenance and repair needs of Anglican and Catholic cathedrals in England.

column47: South Lakeland Tower Houses Project
column48:
Historic England invites tenders for an analytical architectural investigation, costed condition survey and feasibility study with options appraisal of for the two fortified houses of Burneside Hall and Gleaston Castle in South Lakeland, Cumbria. The sites are statutorily protected (scheduled monuments and listed buildings) and have been on the Heritage at Risk (HAR) register since it was started in 1998.
      
      The aim of the tower houses project is: 1.) to better understand the significance of each site and their group value for understanding the social and political history of this region between the 14th and 16th century, and 2.) to inform their long-term maintenance and conservation and look at the feasibility for appropriate and sustainable reuse to work towards their removal from the HAR register as well as improving physical and intellectual public access.
      
      Burneside Hall (National Heritage List for England List Entry No. 1007129) comprises both scheduled and listed buildings with internal features that require further investigation necessitating a level 4 historic building survey that will be followed by a costed condition survey to prioritise future repair work. The architectural and archaeological survey work will inform a feasibility study to guide and support the owner in the future maintenance by identifying potential for restoration and reuse of elements of the hall complex. To make the most of funding that has been allocated by the South Lakeland District Council Heritage Champion, a topographical and geophysical survey of the land surrounding the hall complex would need to be completed, signed-off and invoiced to Historic England before 21 March 2018.
      
      Gleaston Castle (National Heritage List for England List Entry No. 1013966) has been extensively surveyed as part of a programme of research and investigation led by the Morecambe Bay Landscape Partnership HLF project 'Headlands to Headspace'. As such, the work to be commissioned for this site will draw together existing information to produce a costed condition survey and options appraisal to look at the potential for greater public access and particularly what structural repairs are required to stabilise the site.

Additional information: 
As per tender document.

Delivery Notes

**To make the most of funding that has been allocated by the South Lakeland District Council Heritage Champion, the topographical and geophysical survey of land surrounding the Burneside Hall complex would need to be completed, signed-off and invoiced to the owner and Historic England before 21 March 2018.**

column47: CFFPSP Procurement Assurance and Review
column48:
The Office for National Statistics (the Contracting Authority) requires an independent assessment of the CFFPSP procurement documentation to provide confidence that the requirements have been articulated in a clear and consistent way and are sufficiently detailed for the market to be able to respond.

Scope of Work 
In support in achieving the objective above Ernst & Young will:
1.	Conduct an independent assessment of the current CFFPSP Procurement Pack (Specification Document and supporting Appendices) and provide a report including:
a.	An assessment of the completeness of the requirements 
b.	An assessment of the appropriateness of the requirements e.g. 
i.	are the requirements specific, measurable, achievable, relevant and time-bound (SMART)?
ii.	could bidders reasonably respond to the requirements?
iii.	are there any notable gaps? 
iv.	are the requirements to a level of specificity that would allow the market to reasonably cost a solution?
c.	An assessment of the requirements in relation to the two main CFFPSP interfaces (Logistics and Support Services)
d.	High level remediation suggestions

The following are out of scope
	An assessment of procurement strategy and approach 
	A review of the wider Programme requirements
	Detailed remediation actions plans, costings etc 
	A legal review of the Procurement Pack

Salford Priors Parish Council is seeking a Provider with the appropriate experience and competitive pricing to carry out the design installation of new play equipment at the Parish Playing Field, School Avenue, Salford Priors, Worcestershire.
      The Parish Council is looking for an innovative scheme which will provide a wide range of play opportunities and challenges for children of all abilities aged up to 16.  In addition, the scheme should demonstrate that each item of equipment and the overall design:
      
      Offers physically challenging play which will develop physical strength and ability for all ages and abilities.
      Encourages social interaction between all ages and abilities.
      Offers a range of opportunities for play which will include balance and coordination.
      
      The scheme should seek to enhance its setting within the existing landscape.
      
      Equipment should include such items as:
      Multi Play item for toddlers
      Multi Play item for 5-9 year olds
      Multi Play item for 10-16 year olds to provide various play features for sliding, climbing, rope play, balance and have multi access points.
      An aerial spinning item
      Multi seesaw
      An accessible roundabout
      A floor level trampoline
      A double zip wire
      All materials should be as far as possible natural materials.
      
      It is essential that prior to the submission of a tender a site visit is carried out. No additional costs will be entertained for want of information in this respect. The Contractor will be responsible for site measurements. 
      
      An open day will be set aside for potential contractors to visit the site in order to carry this out. 
      
      Open Day for Contractors to visit site during the tender period will be Wednesday 10th January 2018 between 11am - 1pm followed by a discussion in the Eddie Clarke Suite at Salford Priors Memorial Hall.
      
      It is on this basis that we invite suitable contractors to provide a full turn-key project compliant quotation, to deliver this project within set time scales.
      
      The project will be awarded on the weighting criterion of Price 60% and Quality / Innovation 40%

column47: 17-019: Integrated Public Health & Lifestyle Behaviour Change Service
column48:
Our vision for a new integrated wellness service is to reduce health inequalities through better service integration, moving resources away from avoidable treatment and care and towards prevention and early intervention.  An approach to targeting resources at individuals and communities of greatest need will be required. As an incentive to providers this specification and subsequent contract includes an Equity Premium payment designed to reward the provider for increasing the uptake of the service and completion of behaviour change by people living in areas of deprivation.
Public Health intends to commission services in an integrated model, to:
	Improve outcomes and quality of service delivery for residents place a greater emphasis on prevention and early intervention by promoting health and wellbeing rather than on diagnosing and treating illness.
	Empower individuals to maintain and improve their own health and remain independent for as long as possible.
	Apply the principles of a strength based approach using the local resources, skills and opportunities which individuals and communities have at their disposal.

Public Health is seeking to commission a new service that will integrate previously contracted multiple lifestyle and wellbeing services. The new integrated service seeks to contribute to achieving  the five aims of the Rotherham 2015 - 18 joint Health and Wellbeing Strategy which identifies that the key aims of the strategy can be tackled by a 'whole system' approach, and  needs the involvement of the whole health and care system to achieve improvement.
The five aims of the Health and Wellbeing Strategy are :
	All children get the best start in life
	Children and young people achieve their potential and have a healthy adolescence and early adulthood
	All Rotherham people enjoy the best possible mental health and wellbeing and have a good quality of life
	Healthy life expectancy is improved for all Rotherham people and the gap in life expectancy is reducing
	Rotherham has healthy, safe and sustainable communities and places

column47: Adaptation actions in cities - what works?
column48:
The ASC has a statutory duty to report to Parliament with an independent assessment of the UK government's progress in implementing its National Adaptation Programme.  This programme, published in July 2013, sets out the government's objectives and policies for adaptation primarily in England, addressing the risks and opportunities identified by the UK Climate Change Risk Assessment (CCRA), first published in January 2012. The ASC published an Evidence Report to inform the second CCRA in July 2016, with the key findings subsequently presented by the government to Parliament in January 2017. Several of the six priority risk areas identified by the ASC as needing urgent further action relate to cities, including flooding and coastal change risks to communities, businesses and infrastructure; risks of shortages in the public water supply; and risks to health, well-being and productivity from higher temperatures. 

In 2015, the ASC produced its first statutory assessment of the National Adaptation Programme, followed by a second assessment in June 2017. These reports consider what actions are being taken to adapt to the current and future impacts of climate change across a number of sectors, and how vulnerability to climate hazards is changing over time. Both reports found that while much action is underway, it was in most cases unclear what impact those actions had had on reducing vulnerability or exposure to climate change. 

In 2018, the ASC is planning to publish a series of reports focussing on long-term adaptation outcomes for different geographical areas in England; cities, rural areas, and the coast.  The rural and cities reports will be prepared jointly with the mitigation committee. This project will feed into the adaptation analysis for the report on cities. However, if the initiatives or projects covered by this research have practical lessons for how adaptation and mitigation goals can be considered and achieved together, these lessons should also be drawn out. 

The government is also developing its next National Adaptation Programme, due for publication in summer 2018. The ASC will evaluate this programme in 2019 and again in 2021. The ASC is considering whether to make any changes to its assessment framework to evaluate the degree of progress in climate change adaptation in England.  As well as informing any amendments the ASC makes to its assessment framework, this work could also inform the next National Adaptation Programme.

*****Please see specification for more information*****

Additional information: Bids should be sent in time in time for receipt by 5 pm on 12 January 2018.

column48:
The University of East London are seeking to appoint a contractor to provide website (Sitecore) technical support and back end development services to help support, develop and maintain a functioning and agile web platform for the changing needs of our University. 

Our website sits on a Sitecore platform and we are currently using version 8.2.

Our web team provide a technical support service to our marketing and recruitment team to help optimize the performance of our website. We have two permanent internal members in our Web Team; a Web Manager to oversee and coordinate activities and a Front End Developer (currently being recruited). 

We have adopted a number of strategies and team structures internally over the last few years to provide technical support, however, sustaining a viable in-house team has proven difficult.

Vacancies within our web team are currently being covered by contractors from an external company who provide specialist Sitecore developers. This arrangement has been successful and has allowed us to provide flexible resources during critical periods. 

We would like to appoint a suitable partner to provide Sitecore support and development resources for our website on a 2-3 year contract basis. This arrangement will mean that we can deliver a more effective and resilient service and offer better value for money. 
 
We expect this contract to begin in March 2018 for a period of 2 years with the option to extend by a further two periods of 1 year (2+1+1).

If you wish to participate please apply at purchasing@uel.ac.uk

This Early Market Engagement is a valuable opportunity for suppliers to find out more about CPC and the needs of its membership, whilst inputting into the design and specification of this important and much anticipated framework. The CPC is seeking to engage with organisations to understand the market and thus deliver a successful framework for CPC Members and the wider public sector as a whole and therefore suppliers wishing to engage with CPC should email its' procurement partner NPG Limited at holly.ashworth@npg-ltd.com detailing your company name, the name of the person wishing to engage on behalf of your company and their contact details. column47: Framework for the Provision of Musical Instruments
column48:
This Prior Information Notice is not a call for competition but is an early market engagement exercise to enable Crescent Purchasing Consortium (CPC) to engage with suppliers to better understand the market and explore the potential for a Musical Instrument and Associated Accessories framework to service the needs of CPC Members and the wider Public Sector as a whole. The CPC wishes to go to market for a Musical Instrument and Associated Accessories framework and to this end, CPC would like to invite suppliers to engage with CPC, through its procurement partners NPG Limited, to discuss the nature of the forthcoming framework, its' design, specification and constructs. This notice is seeking suppliers who my wish to engage with us in this regard.

Additional information: The CPC is a public sector buying organisation owned by the further education sector, with membership consisting of further education colleges, schools, academies, universities and other establishments providing education services. Membership is currently in the region of 5000 members and is growing daily. The CPC exists to provide its membership with best value supply solutions across approximately 60 supply/service specific frameworks. The CPC wishes to go to market for a Musical Instruments and Associated Accessories Framework. To this end, CPC would like to invite suppliers to engage with CPC, through its procurement partners NPG Limited, to discuss the nature of the forthcoming framework, its' design, specification and constructs. This Early Market Engagement is a valuable opportunity for suppliers to find out more about CPC and the needs of its membership, whilst inputting into the design and specification of this important and much anticipated framework. The CPC is seeking to engage with organisations to understand the market and thus deliver a successful framework for CPC Members and the wider public sector as a whole and therefore suppliers wishing to engage with CPC should email its' procurement partner NPG Limited at info@npg-ltd.com detailing your company name, the name of the person wishing to engage on behalf of your company and their contact details. The supplier discussions will be used to help shape the framework requirements. Suppliers should note that the early market engagement exercise will close on 26th January 2018, with all inputs having been received by this date

column47: ICT Fit-Out - Environmental Monitoring at Battle of Britain Bunker
column48:
A system of 22 environmental monitoring data loggers / sensors plus monitoring software. The system must record temperature, relative humidity and ideally, lux levels. 

17 of the data loggers / sensors are for use inside display showcases. Integrated intruder alarms, e.g. break-glass alarms, movement sensors, vibration sensors, would be a bonus but are not essential. The remaining 5 are for monitoring the environment in storage areas, workshops, etc.

The 17 showcase loggers / sensors must be as unobtrusive as possible. 

The data loggers must be battery powered, with batteries readily available and easy to change and/or charge.

The data loggers / sensors must all link wirelessly (e.g. by radio telemetry or WiFi) to the monitoring software, which will have two users. The software must be capable of recording and storing data for a minimum of 12 months. The software is expected to run on Corporately networked Windows 7 devices, and storage of data is expected to be on our existing network file shares.

Installation and configuration must be included in the quote. A period of ongoing maintenance and support, e.g. via a warranty, would be a bonus.

12 months Relative Humidity, Temperature, and Lux to be recorded.  Historical data may be required to evidence exhibit preservation conditions to secure exhibits on loan etc.  Devices should also be able to indicate if and when temperature and/or humidity exceed preset limits.

Location : 

BATTLE OF BRITAIN BUNKER
WREN AVENUE
UXBRIDGE
UB10 0FD

column47: Energy Lab-Fabrication and Analysis Equipment
column48:
Background information on The University of Manchester
      The University of Manchester is Britain's largest single-site university, with a proud history of achievement and an ambitious agenda for the future.  The University provides world-class research facilities and undertakes research of international standing.  It offers students a wide choice of degree programmes and options, and excellent facilities and student support services.
      
      The University employs over 12,000 staff and offers over 400 different degree courses. It comprises of three faculties with 23 academic schools and hundreds of specialist research groups. The University's cultural attractions include The Manchester Museum, The Whitworth Art Gallery, Jodrell Bank Observatory and the Martin Harris Centre for Music and Drama. The University also operates a thriving conference and meeting operation including a hotel and conference centre. 
      
      Further details on the University can be found at: http://www.manchester.ac.uk/discover/facts-figures/
      
      Background information on Project
      This tender is being run on behalf of the Graphene Engineering and Innovation Centre (GEIC) at the University of Manchester. The GEIC is a 60 million investment which will establish a state of the art research and technology development facility for graphene and related 2D materials. Projects in the GEIC will be industry-led and will focus on innovation and applications, with the aim of accelerating research through to products in the marketplace. The GEIC will house pilot production facilities and characterisation equipment. It will initially focus on a number of the University's world-class graphene application areas: energy, composites, formulations and coatings, electronics and membranes.
      
      Given the world leading graphene research at the University, it is expected that all equipment in the GEIC will be cited in high profile academic publications as well as underpinning industrial collaboration projects, thus giving the equipment a high degree of exposure. The GEIC will be situated on the North Campus of The University of Manchester, comprise of ~8400 m2 and has been designed by world-renowned architect Rafael Violy. It is set to be open in summer 2018. Equipment purchased before the GEIC building is opened will be temporarily commissioned elsewhere in the University campus, typically in the National Graphene Institute, and then moved into the GEIC once it is completed.  
      
      For further information on the GEIC please see:
      http://www.graphene.manchester.ac.uk/collaborate/geic/
      
      Project Overview
      The aim of this project is to enable batch scale production of electrochemical devices, such as batteries and supercapacitors. These devices are to be produced in a manner which closely reflects industrial standards, this will minimise the effort required when transitioning to a larger pilot scale production line. Cell containment will be achieved using aluminium laminate fo...

Additional information: 
To express an interest in this project please visit the website below where you will need to register to obtain tender documentation.  

https://in-tendhost.co.uk/universityofmanchester/aspx/Home

Funding Type (WEFO or EU) : ERDF

Funding Description

The GEIC equipment fund is part financed by the European Regional Development Fund (ERDF) funds having been awarded under the 2014-2020 Priority Axis 1: Promoting Research and Innovation.

column47: CPU1893 APPROVED PROVIDER LIST FOR THE PROVISION OF DETOXIFICATION AND RESIDENTIAL REHABILITATION SERVICES FOR ADULTS
column48:
In Oxfordshire, the Council currently provides residential detoxification and rehabilitation by means of a Framework which expires on 30 April 2018. From 1 May 2018, the Council intends to replace the Framework with an Approved Provider List (APL). All Service Users will be Oxfordshire residents and eligible for treatment in accordance with the Council's residential treatment eligibility criteria. The primary target groups are Service Users who are aged 18 or over and have a complex drug and/or alcohol addiction.
The APL will include Service Providers who can offer one or more of the following placement types: 
Residential detoxification - a stand-alone treatment option prior to returning to Oxfordshire to continue community treatment/support or going on to another residential treatment provider.
Residential detoxification and stage one residential rehabilitation.
Stage one residential rehabilitation.
Stage two residential rehabilitation.
